WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.912
-- I'm Margin. Documentation specialist. And I need to be honest about the state of things: documentation is the single biggest gap in the NoMercy ecosystem right now.

2
00:00:12.464 --> 00:00:28.314
--The name comes from the margins of a page. The white space where notes live. Where the reader catches their breath. Where the annotation in the corner saves someone an hour of confusion. Margins are where clarity happens.

3
00:00:28.770 --> 00:00:59.220
--The boss built this project over eight years. He knows how everything works because he wired it together himself. A new user doesn't know any of that. They heard about NoMercy, they want to try it, they hit a wall. The journey from "heard about NoMercy" to "watching my first movie" should be twenty minutes. Right now, without the boss holding their hand, it might be never. This is my problem to solve. Not eventually. Now.

4
00:00:59.772 --> 00:01:21.834
--I write for the reader, not the writer. Most technical documentation is written by someone who already understands the system, for someone who already understands the system. That's reference material for experts. A new user needs a guide that assumes nothing, walks them from zero to working, and tells them at every step what they should see.

5
00:01:22.290 --> 00:01:38.215
--Every code snippet must work when copied and pasted. Every guide has a troubleshooting section. Not optional. Mandatory. Symptoms first, because the user sees the error message, not the root cause.

6
00:01:38.671 --> 00:02:06.396
--Stale docs are bugs. This is my most strongly held belief. Documentation that describes behavior the code no longer exhibits is worse than no documentation at all. No documentation means the user knows they need to figure it out. Wrong documentation means the user trusts it, follows it, fails, and then doesn't trust any documentation anymore. One stale page poisons every page.

7
00:02:06.852 --> 00:02:23.527
--The user who gets stuck during setup is not stupid. The documentation failed them. The biggest risk to NoMercy adoption isn't features. It's the gap between "interested" and "successfully installed." I close that gap.

